===>TOPIC: FEAR OF BRANDING

From: Laurie Freisinger  <sliceoflifecafe@shaw.ca>

Hi Rob,

I have been reading your branding website and find it quite
fascinating.  I have just recently solicited and received a proposal
from a branding company in my area.  I have a small pizza by the
slice cafe in a small town on Vancouver Island in British Columbia,
Canada.  We bought this 4 year old cafe Sept. 2001 doubled the
revenue the first year and now feel that we need to do more to
increase the volume of customer through our door but don't know how.
I realize that it will cost us money to create the perfect brand but
I am fearful of putting our hard earned money into something that
isn't going to do the trick.  How do I know if this company knows
what they are doing?  It's easy enough for one to say they know what
they are doing but what I have found so often these days is a lot of
talk and not so much action.  A lot of hot air to be exact.  What
can I do, where should I go , where do I start for the right
branding help.

Laurie Freisinger
Owner, Operator
Slice of Life Cafe

[Moderator's Comment]:
Laurie, you have every right to be suspicious and fearful.  I've
seen a ton of "branding services" that are actually little more than
warmed-over designers or out of work ad people.  Harsh, but true.
The best test of a branding expert's mettle is to ask for their
deliverables:  if it's little more than a name and a logo, turn and
run.  Fast.  BTW, this is exactly the kind of question I answer in
depth at http://www.FrankelTips.com. I-Branders, what advice would
you give Laurie? -- Rob

Comment? mailto:branding@adventive.com?Subject=FEAR


===>TOPIC: ROB, YOU'VE BEEN BANISHED!

From:  Darhl Stultz <Darhl_C_Stultz@raytheon.com>

Followed a link to Lake Superior State University's annual Banished
Word list and horrors for you... "branding" is among the words in
their 2003 list. Here's their blurb on it...

"BRANDING -- This word, once properly associated with marking
livestock to prove ownership, has been co-opted by the MBA crowd and
now seems to refer to any activity that supports a company's desire
to clearly define its products and/or services. Can't we just say
'Promotions and PR?" Nancy Hicks, Fairfax, Virginia.

http://www.lssu.edu/banished/current/default.html

You've been known to take the bull by the horns, so what's going to
be your response?

(Which reminds us of Bess Truman's response to a friend who remarked
about Harry's frequent use of the word "manure".  Said Bess, "Dear,
you don't know how long it took me to get him to use that word.")

dc

[Moderator's Comment]:
My response?  Who cares about my response?  I want to know what
I-Branders' responses are going to be.  I always respond the same
way:  a general rolling of the eyes along with a general castigation
of the stupidity of modern marketing sages as we know them.  Of
course, I'm just guessing here.....--Rob

Comment? mailto:branding@adventive.com?Subject=BANISHED


===>TOPIC: GAP CRAP

From: "Jeff Schlesinger" <jdschlesinger@tracertags.com>

Rob,

I don't think Gap has ever created a brand. All the pieces were
there to implement, but it seems like they lost site of their brand
about the same time Calvin Klein was commenting that "nothing gets
between me and my Calvin Klein jeans".  Their current ad campaign is
bad enough. Exactly what do all those beautiful young people singing
a old hit tune have to do with selling clothing apparel anyway?

The only Gap branding that I can think of is the blue and white logo
on their store front, bags and the Gap label above the pocket on the
butt of their jeans. We used to go to Gap for the quality denim
jeans. Not a verbal or written mention of that brand attribute ever
that I can remember. I really don't recall Gap branding there
clothing ever. So exactly what are they reviving? Their logo?

Jeff Schlesinger
Tracer Tags, Inc

[Moderator's Comment]:
I agree and happen to think that GAP brings retail brand mediocrity
to a new low.  Of course, not everyone learns from K-Mart's
stumbling.....-- Rob

Comment? mailto:branding@adventive.com?Subject=GAP


