===>TOPIC: SELF BRANDING

From: Lynn <lynn@ecgincc.com>

Mitch, I can't answer your question on self branding, but I did
notice something interesting about marketers. I attended a holiday
networking party sponsored by a state-level association. With the
exception of one techie, everyone else I met was a marketing person.
I exchanged cards with several, at my instigation. I am still
wondering why none of the marketing people did.

I noticed on the cards I collected, the people working for a major
corp had cards with their own domain names and email addresses using
their domain names. Others did not have a domain name for their
business. Still others had a domain name for a web site, but used
their ISP domain name for email.

The Association website has a logo of the web development company
that created the site. I do not use IE. I could not see much of the
site.

The networking party was Thursday evening. As I have been busy, I
didn't have time to send email to those I had an email address. I
did this morning.

Not one of the 'marketing' people sent me an email. None have
replied to my email (several hours later). I received one reply -
from the techie.

My conclusion - we could teach the experts a lot about marketing and
branding (oh yes, there were branding people there too - included in
the cards I received)

Draw your own conclusions as to their expertise.

Oh Rob, I gave one person your addy, and followed up with it in
email. A branding 'expert' that has no clue about online branding.

Lynn Bernstein
ECG Consulting
http://www.ecg-incc.com

[Moderator's Comment]:
Are surprised?  I think not.  Lynn's experience only goes to show
what I've said all along:  branding is the most misunderstood
discipline in all of marketing.  Oh, also that all referrals are
welcome. -- Rob

Comment? mailto:branding@adventive.com?Subject=SELF


===>TOPIC: SELF BRANDING

From: "Mitch Joel" <mitch@twistimage.com>

Thanks for some of the insight. One of the main reasons I wrote the
initial email was to spark a conversation. We're presently re-doing
a lot of the issues brought up in Arlene's comments. Our company has
a desperate need to balance good, strong and valid content with
killer design.

The idea of self-branding is difficult for us to let go of because
a) we are very creative and are looking forward to taking many
people's advice as to the new "play" of the site and b) all too
often you'll see sites that dazzle the eyes with little content
(like the current Twist Image website) or sites that are all content
are fairly poorly designed. I think the challenge we all face is to
show people - in a very web-friendly way - how the process of the
business works and what it "smells" like without actually walking
into our studio space.

I'm still challenged by the concept of letting another marketing
company walk through our doors when, by simply looking at their
sites and services, they do not have the necessary balance of
design, content and technology. It's a big plate of food to eat and
I'm not entirely confident that we, as marketers, truly show our
clients what they can do. Specifically, by showing the client via
what we've done for ourselves.

Another opportunity for thoughts and comments... ;)

Mitch Joel
Twist Image
http://www.twistimage.com

[MODERATOR'S COMMENT]:
http://www.robfrankel.com/frankelaws.html

Comment? mailto:branding@adventive.com?Subject=SELF


===>TOPIC: AWARENESS VS. SALES

From: "Eddy Budianto" <herr@centrin.net.id>

Dear I-Branders,

Recently I just read Sergio Book's : The End of Advertising as we
know it.

At that book, He mentioned that brand awareness is useless if it not
increase the sales. Sure it is. the point is when you advertise,
build the brand and etc, you have to make sure that you explain to
the customer why they should buy your brand. It means that all
advertisement, promotion etc which could add brand awareness is
totally useless if it not increase the sales.

The topic are : Is it possible we could sell the product without
brand awareness? The point is true that many people know about HONDA
but how many people will buy HONDA compare to its competitor. If
product A's brand awareness is higher than product B's brand, it
doesn't mean its sales higher too.. so.. what is the ideal way in
this case? according to Sergio, it is only one... that is you have
to tell customer why they must buy your brand. it sure is.. but how?

Rgrds,
Eddy

Comment? mailto:branding@adventive.com?Subject=AWARENESS


===>TOPIC: BRAND RESPONSIBILITY

From: Arlene Teck <rlene@rcn.com>

As it happens, I am with Allen on the McDonald's thing. Even though
I personally prefer Wendy's, many, many people eat McDonald's
hamburgers and do not get ill.

Rather, it is the combination of things we eat over our lifetimes
that may make us ill, and no one is to "blame" for that, except
ourselves. Carried to the logical conclusion, no restaurant could
afford to be in business unless it carried its own form of
malpractice insurance and required all patrons to sign waivers.
Ridiculous!

That fat kid and his lawyer are pulling a scam -- and the more
people who know it, the better!

As it happens, I get migraine headaches from eating the chocolate
bits in chocolate chip cookies. A sad state of affairs for me -- but
I am not suing Nestlé's!

Of course, social responsibility is more of a good thing than not,
but in essence, I believe, it begins at home -- with the choices we
make about our own lives.

Sign me: "Aunty Litigation"
Arlene Teck

KickStart your marketing efforts with KickButt Branding<TM>
For Striking Power and Staying Power

Comment? mailto:branding@adventive.com?Subject=RESPONSIBILITY


